  "text": "CLPTM1L encodes an enzyme, cleft lip and palate transmembrane 1-like that is upregulated in lung cancer tissues and may be associated with anti-apoptotic mechanism which affects the resistance to chemotherapy. [CITATION_1] Experimental studies also showed that CLPTM1L promotes growth and survival, and is required for KRAS driven lung cancer. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] Genetic variants within the CLPTM1L have been found to be associated with the accumulation of DNA adducts in tumor adjacent lung tissue [CITATION_4] and contribute to the susceptibility of lung cancer in multiple GWASs. [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] In the current study, we identified an intronic variant in CLPTM1L, rs397640, was associated lung cancer risk. Rs397640 was in the same LD block with rs401681 (r 2 50.16, D'50.95), a lung cancer associated SNV identified in multiple GWASs. [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] The association observed for rs397640 was slightly attenuated but remained statistical significant after accounting for rs401681 (p 5 4.0 3 10",
